Thunder could be without Steven Adams, Carmelo Anthony against Bulls

by Erik Horne Published: November 14, 2017 2:36 PM CDT Updated: November 14, 2017 3:06 PM CDT
5 shares
facebook twitter pinterest email 0 comments
Advertisement

The Thunder’s second meeting with the Chicago Bulls this season could be another starting opportunity for Dakari Johnson and Jerami Grant.

At Tuesday’s shootaround, Thunder coach Billy Donovan said he doesn’t expect Steven Adams to play against the Bulls, and that Carmelo Anthony will be evaluated again on Wednesday. Adams has missed the last two games with a right calf contusion he suffered Nov. 9 against Denver. Anthony was a late scratch from Sunday’s win against Dallas with a sore lower back.

Anthony was non-contact and did some light shooting in post-practice on Tuesday, while Adams did not practice.

“Unless something changes at shootaround I don’t expect him to play,” Donovan said of Adams. “That’s not to say he won’t, but that’s just my feeling right now coming off today’s practice.

"I asked after practice what’s the likelihood of him being able to go through shootaround and the game tomorrow, and they didn’t think there was a really good likelihood, but they were optimistic that he continues to get better and improve."

Johnson, a rookie, has started the last two games for the Thunder at center, averaging seven points, two rebounds, an assist and a block in 20.1 minutes per game. Grant started at power forward for Anthony on Sunday and logged 10 points (3-of-6 field goals), eight rebounds and three assists in 34 minutes.

Donovan didn't know whether or not Adams would be available for the Thunder's next two games on the road against two formidable front lines. The Thunder plays at San Antonio on Friday and at New Orleans on Sunday.

Erik Horne

Thunder could be without Steven Adams, Carmelo Anthony against Bulls

by Erik Horne Published: November 14, 2017 2:36 PM CDT Updated: November 14, 2017 3:06 PM CDT
5 shares
facebook twitter pinterest email 0 comments
Advertisement

The Thunder’s second meeting with the Chicago Bulls this season could be another starting opportunity for Dakari Johnson and Jerami Grant.

At Tuesday’s shootaround, Thunder coach Billy Donovan said he doesn’t expect Steven Adams to play against the Bulls, and that Carmelo Anthony will be evaluated again on Wednesday. Adams has missed the last two games with a right calf contusion he suffered Nov. 9 against Denver. Anthony was a late scratch from Sunday’s win against Dallas with a sore lower back.

Anthony was non-contact and did some light shooting in post-practice on Tuesday, while Adams did not practice.

“Unless something changes at shootaround I don’t expect him to play,” Donovan said of Adams. “That’s not to say he won’t, but that’s just my feeling right now coming off today’s practice.

"I asked after practice what’s the likelihood of him being able to go through shootaround and the game tomorrow, and they didn’t think there was a really good likelihood, but they were optimistic that he continues to get better and improve."

Johnson, a rookie, has started the last two games for the Thunder at center, averaging seven points, two rebounds, an assist and a block in 20.1 minutes per game. Grant started at power forward for Anthony on Sunday and logged 10 points (3-of-6 field goals), eight rebounds and three assists in 34 minutes.

In two games without Adams, the Thunder's defense has allowed 102.9 points per 100 possessions, more than four points higher than its season average of 98.5. The Thunder's offense, meanwhile, has scored a league-best 118.0 points per 100 possessions with Adams out, 111.9 without Adams and Anthony last game, both higher than its season average of 104.1.

Donovan didn't know whether or not Adams would be available for the Thunder's next two games on the road against two formidable front lines. The Thunder plays at San Antonio on Friday and at New Orleans on Sunday.

Thunder could be without Steven Adams, Carmelo Anthony against Bulls

by Erik Horne Published: November 14, 2017 2:36 PM CDT Updated: November 14, 2017 3:06 PM CDT
5 shares
facebook twitter pinterest email 0 comments
Advertisement

The Thunder’s second meeting with the Chicago Bulls this season could be another starting opportunity for Dakari Johnson and Jerami Grant.

At Tuesday’s shootaround, Thunder coach Billy Donovan said he doesn’t expect Steven Adams to play against the Bulls, and that Carmelo Anthony will be evaluated again on Wednesday. Adams has missed the last two games with a right calf contusion he suffered Nov. 9 against Denver. Anthony was a late scratch from Sunday’s win against Dallas with a sore lower back.

Anthony was non-contact and did some light shooting in post-practice on Tuesday, while Adams did not practice.

“Unless something changes at shootaround I don’t expect him to play,” Donovan said of Adams. “That’s not to say he won’t, but that’s just my feeling right now coming off today’s practice.

"I asked after practice what’s the likelihood of him being able to go through shootaround and the game tomorrow, and they didn’t think there was a really good likelihood, but they were optimistic that he continues to get better and improve."

Johnson, a rookie, has started the last two games for the Thunder at center, averaging seven points, two rebounds, an assist and a block in 20.1 minutes per game. Grant started at power forward for Anthony on Sunday and logged 10 points (3-of-6 field goals), eight rebounds and three assists in 34 minutes.

In two games without Adams, the Thunder's defense has allowed 102.9 points per 100 possessions, more than four points higher than its season average of 98.5. The Thunder's offense, meanwhile, has scored a league-best 118.0 points per 100 possessions with Adams out, 111.9 without Adams and Anthony last game, both higher than its season average of 104.1.

Donovan didn't know whether or not Adams would be available for the Thunder's next two games on the road against two formidable front lines. The Thunder plays at San Antonio on Friday and at New Orleans on Sunday.

Erik Horne
